records.addlTxt:
Defendant Joevena L Porter in court with attorney Alejandro A. Lockwood.  James W. Frisch appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.   The Court imposed one (1) year at the House of Correction, with good time and release to the Day Reporting Center and child care release.  Credit for 5 days time served.  Court STAYED said sentence and placed defendant on probation for 18 months.
 * Court ordered defendant to provide DNA sample.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
 - Undergo a mental health evaluation; follow thru with any treatment recommended;
 - No controlled substances other than those legally prescribed for defendant by a duly licensed physcian for her mental or physical needs; take all medications as described;
 - No alcohol; 
 - Urine screens;
 - AODA assessement; treatment if needed;
 - Seek and maintain employment;
 - Be given job and vocational training;
 - Anger management counseling/classes;
 - Parenting classes/counseling;
 - No contact with Lt. William Kowalski;
 - Obtain GED;
 - Cognitive thinking intervention counseling;
 - Pay the DNA surcharge, plus all costs, surcharges and disbursements.  Failure to pay would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant.

Should defendant complete all conditions set forth by the Court and the Probation Department, pay all court costs and surchages as ordered,  and remain free and clear of the criminal justice system arising to the level of probable cause, the Court would consider petition for expungement.

Filed,
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief;
Pretrial Incarceration Credit;
Letter in support of defendant.
